2v.title: Value Alignment Theory
2v.text:
Clickbait:  The great civilizational problem of creating AIs such that running them is a good idea.

Summary:  "Value alignment theory" is the overarching research topic of how to develop a highly advanced Artificial Intelligence such that running this AI produces good real-world outcomes.  Other terms that have been used to describe this research subject are "robust and beneficial [superintelligence]" and "Friendly AI theory".

Where to go first if you're just coming in and want to poke around:  [List of Value Alignment Topics](3g).

For a nontechnical introduction to the field, see [todo].  For a tutorial introduction, see [todo].  (These don't exist yet.  Meanwhile, if you have no idea what this is all about, try reading Nick Bostrom's book Superintelligence?)

For an organized list of topics within this subject, see the current [list of value alignment topics](3g).

For the definition of 'value alignment' as contrasted to 'value identification' or 'value achievement', see the page on [value alignment problem](5s).  For the definition of 'value' as a metasyntactic placeholder for "the still-debated thing we want our AIs to accomplish", see the page on [value](55).

2w.clickbait: When you ask the AI to make people happy, and it tiles the universe with the smallest objects that can be happy.

2x.title: Omnipotence test for AI safety
2x.clickbait: Would your AI produce disastrous outcomes if it suddenly gained omnipotence and omniscience? If so, why did you program something that *wants* to hurt you and is held back only by lacking the power?

2y.title: Relevant limited AI
2y.clickbait: Can we have a limited AI, that's nonetheless relevant?

2z.title: Value achievement dilemma
2z.clickbait: How can Earth-originating intelligent life achieve most of its potential value, whether by AI or otherwise?

3c5.title: Coherent extrapolated volition (alignment target)
3c5.clickbait: A proposed direction for an extremely well-aligned autonomous superintelligence - do what humans would want, if we knew what the AI knew, thought that fast, and understood ourselves.

4w.clickbait: What do a "red strawberry", a "red apple", and a "red cherry" have in common that a "yellow carrot" doesn't?  Are they "red fruits" or "red objects"?

5b.clickbait: How and why to use precise language and words with special meaning when talking about value alignment.

5f.title: Preference framework
5f.clickbait: What's the thing an agent uses to compare its preferences?

5g.title: Diamond maximizer
5g.clickbait: How would you build an agent that made as much diamond material as possible, given vast computing power but an otherwise rich and complicated environment?

5j.title: Distant superintelligences can coerce the most probable environment of your AI
5j.clickbait: Distant superintelligences may be able to hack your local AI, if your AI's preference framework depends on its most probable environment.

5l.title: Complexity of value
5l.clickbait: There's no simple way to describe the goals we want Artificial Intelligences to want.

5s.title: Value alignment problem
5s.clickbait: You want to build an advanced AI with the right values... but how?

5t.title: Object-level vs. indirect goals
5t.clickbait: Difference between "give Alice the apple" and "give Alice what she wants".

5v.title: Algorithmic complexity
5v.clickbait: When you compress the information, what you are left with determines the complexity.

6q.title: Context disaster
6q.clickbait: Some possible designs cause your AI to behave nicely while developing, and behave a lot less nicely when it's smarter.

6r.title: Methodology of foreseeable difficulties
6r.clickbait: Building a nice AI is likely to be hard enough, and contain enough gotchas that won't show up in the AI's early days, that we need to foresee problems coming in advance.

6v.title: Mindcrime
6v.clickbait: Might a machine intelligence contain vast numbers of unhappy conscious subprocesses?

6w.title: Task-directed AGI
6w.clickbait: An advanced AI that's meant to pursue a series of limited-scope goals given it by the user.  In Bostrom's terminology, a Genie.

7g0.title: Non-adversarial principle
7g0.clickbait: At no point in constructing an Artificial General Intelligence should we construct a computation that tries to hurt us, and then try to stop it from hurting us.

7g1.title: Sufficiently advanced Artificial Intelligence
7g1.clickbait: 'Sufficiently advanced Artificial Intelligences' are AIs with enough 'advanced agent properties' that we start needing to do 'AI alignment' to them.

7hh.title: Coherent decisions imply consistent utilities
7hh.clickbait: Why do we all use the 'expected utility' formalism?  Because any behavior that can't be viewed from that perspective, must be qualitatively self-defeating (in various mathy ways).

7v8.title: Principles in AI alignment
7v8.clickbait: A 'principle' of AI alignment is a very general design goal like 'understand what the heck is going on inside the AI' that has informed a wide set of specific design proposals.

7vg.title: Theory of (advanced) agents
7vg.clickbait: One of the research subproblems of building powerful nice AIs, is the theory of (sufficiently advanced) minds in general.

8dh.title: Difficulty of AI alignment
8dh.clickbait: How hard is it exactly to point an Artificial General Intelligence in an intuitively okay direction?

9m.clickbait: Words that have a special meaning in the context of creating nice AIs.
